#block[
SU(2)\] In this case there is a good convergence among different
published results both for the string tension and for the critical
temperature. Data on #mi(`T_c`) are reported in~[tc1] for lattices with
length #mi(`L=2`) in the imaginary time direction; in~[tc2] for
#mi(`L=4`) and in~[tc3] for #mi(`L=5`) and 6. Scaling seems to be
fulfilled already for #mi(`L>4`) and allows a rather precise estimation:
#mi(`T_c\beta a=1.4\pm0.1`)~[tc3] (where #mi(`a`) is the lattice spacing
and #mi(`\beta`) the inverse of the coupling constant). Data on
#mi(`\sigma`) are reported in~[sigma1] and more recently in~[sigma2], in
both case obtained with Wilson loops. Scaling seems to be fulfilled
already for #mi(`\beta>6.`) (in agreement with the #mi(`T_c`)
behaviour). These two sets of data agree and give
#mi(`\sigma(\beta a)^2=2.23\pm0.04`). This implies
#mi(`T_c/\sqrt{\sigma}=0.94\pm0.03`) in agreement with our critical
temperature for the minimal radius #mi(`r_1`),
#mi(`T_c/{\sqrt\sigma}={\sqrt3}/{\sqrt\pi}=0.98`). Indeed this result
was already presented in~[fp] to support the Nambu-Goto string picture,
and has not been significatively changed by the new high precision data
of ref~[sigma2.]

#mi(`Z_2`)\] In this case a rather precise estimate exists for the
string tension ~[noiz2]~:
#mi(`\sigma a^2(\beta_c-\beta)^{-2\nu}=3.64\pm0.09`)~, with
#mi(`\beta_c=0.7614`) and #mi(`\nu=0.63`). For the critical temperature,
the scaling region seems to start from #mi(`L=4`). Data obtained with
the Montecarlo renormalization group approach~[wan2] for #mi(`L=4,8`),
give #mi(`T_c a(\beta_c-\beta)^{-\nu}
=2.3\pm0.1`), while a slightly lower value was obtained using finite
size scaling techniques~[wan1][brower] for #mi(`L=4`):
#mi(`T_c a(\beta_c-\beta)^{-\nu}=2.2\pm0.1`). Taking into account all
the uncertainties we can assume: #mi(`T_c/\sqrt{\sigma}=1.17\pm0.1`)
which is in acceptable agreement with our solution.

]
